Nowhere in the Frankenwald was a place so shaped by the railway.
Here was the starting point of the steep ramp mountain route to the north, which has its apex in Steinbach am Wald after an ascent of about 220 meters altitude.
To cope with this, train and push locomotives were used to be needed, which had their home in Pressig.
In 1901, the Bavarian state parliament approved the construction of a railway workshop with 21 locomotive sheds, apprentice workshop, overhead line and railway mastery.
"The centrepiece was the hub, which had a diameter of 18 meters after a conversion in 1899," says Norbert Heidrich from Hirschaid, railway historian and professional railway operator for 47 years.
The railway depot (BW) Pressig, which was subordinated to Bamberg in 1968, also operated locomotives for the secondary lines Pressig - Tettau, Ludwigsstadt - Lehesten, Stockheim - Sonneberg and Kronach - Nordhalben.
On the 15th In July 1950, the "Volksblatt" reported a staff of 160 men; 13 steam and eight elloks were stationed in Pressig at the time.
The electrification of the line in 1939 already minimized the need for train and push locomotives.
From 1977, they were only used for freight trains.
Until 1991, at least 10 000 wagons were still ranked per month.
In 1982, parts of the plant were demolished, in 1991 the rest.
Heidrich: "It is unfortunate that you have not envisaged a better use of the location, also in terms of freight transport."
At Pentecost 1989, the Nuremberg Railway Directorate celebrated a pompous station festival in Pressig for the anniversary of "50 Years of Electrification Nuremberg - Saalfeld".
"There were 10 000 enthusiastic spectators here," recalls Georg Dinkel.
A little later the end.
On the 1. June 1991 the last 30 men were withdrawn, the shunting yard Pressig was history.
"The shunters and inhibitors did the most difficult work in train traffic," recalls Dinkel.
