Farmers are allowed to start annual kinking care on Monday
Schleswig-Holstein's farmers are allowed to begin annual kink care on Monday.
The "green ramparts" unique in Germany have shaped the landscape of the forest-poor state for around 200 years.
The tree and scrub chuckles, which are up to five metres wide, are "forest substitutes" and the last retreats for many animals and plants.
Knicks connect scattered habitats as corridors, over which the exchange of organisms can still work, as the managing director of the Naturschutzbund Deutschland (NABU) in Schleswig-Holstein, Ingo Ludwichowski, said.
Knicks are living fences
The Knicks were created on the basis of an order of the Danish King Christian VI in 1766, which ruled Schleswig-Holstein.
The "living fences" were not only field boundary and cattle fence, they also provided the farmers with firewood and beams for their half-timbered houses.
His name "Knick" also comes from that time: by "buckling" the branches, the dense, intertwined demarcations could develop.
Today, around 45 000 kilometres of hedges extend between the North Sea and the Baltic Sea and give the image of a wood-rich, diversely structured landscape.
According to the NABU, they are now used by around 7000 animal species as a substitute habitat.
Up to 1800 different species could live in a kilometre of kink and breed up to 30 pairs of birds.
However, the kink can only fulfil its ecologically important function if it is maintained accordingly in winter.
Otherwise, he stunts to a light row of trees, which, in addition to biodiversity, also loses the wind protection effect, Ludwichowski said.
According to the Ministry of Agriculture, the kink care may only be operated outside the breeding season from October to March.
