Building in Landsham: 100 applications for 20 plots
The need is apparently huge: over 100 interested parties have applied for the purchase of one of the plots in Landsham-South.
The municipality of Pliening has sold the first plots of land in the new development area Landsham-Süd on the open market.
This is announced by Mayor Roland Frick.
In addition, the application phase for those 20 plots of land that the municipality is completed on more favorable conditions or Prices offered - similar to the previous local model.
A good 100 applications were received, according to Frick.
"Currently, the documents are being checked" with regard to the application criteria, completeness and correctness.
According to the mayor of Plieningen, the aim is to have drawn up the applicant rankings for the 20 properties by the end of the year and to submit them to the local council.
After that, the award can be made.
A total of 50 plots of land for single and semi-detached houses will be created on the site in the south of Landsham, as well as four areas for apartment buildings with eight residential units each.
The development is now almost complete, the roads and paths are to be paved soon.
A single plot and two of the apartment buildings belong to a private individual, the rest of the municipality of Pliening.
It sells the majority on the open market, 20 plots in the socially acceptable model.
The two apartment buildings of the municipality are to be built as affordable housing, according to Frick.
With a total of 16 income-oriented housing funded by the Free State.
Space for 200 people
Roughly estimated, housing for about 200 people is created on the area of the Landsham-Süd new development area.
Not only that: Now, at the beginning of October, according to Frick, the start of a new daycare center is taking place there.
It will house three kindergarten and three crib groups as well as a multi-purpose room.
The opening is scheduled for September 2019, at the start of the next kindergarten year.
This is how Schalke's Naldo "great sport" succeeds even on the bench
For the third time in a row not in the starting eleven: Naldo nevertheless thanks Schalke coach Domenico Tedesco.
Gelsenkirchen - After Ronaldo Aparecido Rodrigues had sat for the third time in a row not in the Schalk starting eleven, but on the bench, the understanding would have been great for many people, if the almost two-meter-tall Brazilian had really talked the frustration of the soul.
But when the Schalk players gathered in the middle circle as usual after the 1:0 win over FSV Mainz 05 and thanked head coach Domenico Tedesco to all his pros, the 36-year-old, whom everyone simply calls Naldo, intervened and said; "We have to thank, coach!"
"That was very emotional, that was great sport," Tedesco later said of the reaction to his vice-captain, who had no grudges despite his renewed reservist existence.
Probably Nildo, who was hailed as best Schalker last season, knows that he actually did not get on the siding at his coach - but for good reasons is getting a break.
A reason called "burden control."
It was not easy to tell him this
"It wasn't easy to tell him that, I'll tell you that quite honestly," Tedesco reported of the moment he told Naldo that he wasn't in the starting eleven.
He's an important player, he's an important person.
But it's always about the matter, it's about the club," Tedesco justified the move.
Naldo has played 90 minutes against Bayern and Porto.
He is 36 years old.
It is important that everyone can breathe at the moment.
And that we all keep in the boat," Tedesco explained of the rotation, which has also caught Naldo recently.
And to which the Brazilian responded with the wisdom of his advanced age: by also proving himself to be an exemplary team player on the bench.
The mood in Austria's industry continued its decline in August compared to the eurozone.
The Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) was at a 37-month low at 46.7 points.
Europe-wide, Austria nevertheless has the third best mood behind Ireland and the Netherlands, the Markit Institute announced on Monday on its survey of 3,000 companies.
Unlike in Austria, the PMI of the euro zone rose by 1.1 to 45.1 points, the index is still the 13th. Month in a row below the mark of 50 meters, which indicates growth.
Only Ireland's industry cracked that threshold in August with 50.9 points.
The Greeks were the final light (42.1 points).
In Germany, France and Spain, the mood barometer dropped, but more slowly than in the months before.
In Spain, the index reached its highest level since March at 44.0 points.
"The slightly weakened descent could mean that the worst is over," said Markit economist Rob Dobson.
However, the industry remains - in the third quarter at least - growth brake number one.
A rapid return to the growth zone is not in sight: export orders in the eurozone fell as much as they have not since November 2011.
The companies therefore cut jobs for the seventh month in a row.
Industrial production in China also fell more sharply in August than initially thought.
The sentiment barometer fell to 47.6 points from 49.3 points the previous month.
Experts had initially expected 47.8 points.
The Purchasing Managers' Index bases its figures on representative surveys of 3,000 European industrial companies.
Developments in sales, employment, warehouses and prices are highlighted, among other things.
